    <chapter id="glossary" title="Glossary">
        <p>A definition list or a glossary:</p>
        <deflist>
            <def id="aesthetics" title="Aesthetics">
                Aesthetics (also spelled esthetics) is the branch of philosophy concerned with the nature of beauty and
                the nature of taste; and functions as the philosophy of art. Aesthetics examines the philosophy of
                aesthetic value, which is determined by critical judgments of artistic taste; thus, the function of
                aesthetics is the "critical reflection on art, culture and nature".
            </def>
            <def id="composition" title="composition">
                The term composition means "putting together". It can be thought of as the organization of the elements
                of art according to the principles of art. Composition can apply to any work of art, from music through
                writing and into photography, that is arranged using conscious thought.
            </def>
            <def id="erotic" title="Erotic">
                Erotic photography is a style of art photography of an erotic, sexually suggestive or sexually
                provocative nature.
            </def>
            <def id="fine-art-photography" title="Fine-art photography">
                Fine-art photography is photography created in line with the vision of the photographer as artist, using
                photography as a medium for creative expression. The goal of fine-art photography is to express an idea,
                a message, or an emotion. This stands in contrast to representational
            </def>
            <def id="glamour-photography" title="Glamour photography">
                Glamour photography is a genre of photography in which the subjects are portrayed in erotic poses
                ranging from fully clothed to nude. The focus lies in the beauty of the subject's body; as such, beauty
                standards are often a key determinant of glamour model trends.
            </def>
